"I genuinely love VALORANT’s worldbuilding, lore, agents—pretty much everything about its universe. But looking at it now, I can’t help feeling like Riot just isn’t taking the story side of the game seriously enough.
The lore feels like it has so much depth on the surface, but once you really try to dig into it, there’s often not much there. It looks fascinating, but in the end it rarely goes anywhere meaningful.
And lately, it feels like more and more agents are being introduced as little more than plot devices—like Tejo, Waylay, and others. Back in the early days, almost every agent had their own unique reason and story for joining the VALORANT Protocol. Now it feels like half of them just get brought in through someone else’s recommendation.
I really hope every agent can have their own distinct story instead of just becoming background dust—filling plot holes or existing to support and highlight the more popular characters.
On top of that, the storytelling itself is starting to feel way too formulaic. It’s getting predictable, and honestly, less interesting.
And can we please talk about the way the story is delivered? The current narrative style is way too fragmented. Fragmented storytelling can work—but not when it feels this scattered and half-hearted all the time.
Please don’t forget about those of us who actually care about the lore.",Vent,"Label is a little unclear because the user names specific examples, but ultimately, they are not concrete examples (likely also because lore can be interpreted subjectively). This is why I classified it as vent."
"With the upcoming buffs to all of Killjoy’s basic utility, I’m fully expecting her to be meta once again, going back to her days in 2022 as the most played Sentinel, and because Riot seems to focus quite a bit on her post-plant power with the molly duration buffs, I’m expecting Veto to be quite a good counter to Killjoy.

First point: Killjoy’s ultimate is a 9 point ultimate which disables all players on a site, we all know that. And Veto’s ultimate which a 7 points ultimate making him immune to all utility other than bullets/knifes, meaning Veto will almost always have his ultimate when Killjoy has hers, which fully counters Killjoy’s plan to isolate sites.

Second point: Killjoy players tend to use their utility close to the entrance/on the spike for post-plants. With the upcoming cooldown buff for Veto’s Interceptor, he will almost always be able clear out all utility around the entrance/spike before Killjoys can activate it, unless it’s pre-activated.

Third point: Killjoy players are lurkers, a global trip that can only be avoided with a smoke, is usually terrible for Killjoy, she either needs to reveal her position by shooting it, or wait until Veto dies/is disabled for finding a timing. In the highest ranks it will also be noted that Killjoy might gotten past the trip if Veto’s dead/disabled.

The only Con, to Veto is that he has no proper way of avoiding killjoy Turrets without teleporting past it, and unless he knows Killjoy’s positioning, Killjoy will always hear the audio of the crosscut.

If you are worried about Killjoy becoming META, I highly suggest picking up Veto this act. It will very likely earn you some RR.
