"Rank Distribution shows you how many people are in your specific bucket. Top% tells you your percentile aka how many players you’ve mathematically surpassed.

Top% in Valorant (EU):

Radiant Top 0.02%

Immortal 3 Top 0.14%

Immortal 2 Top 0.37%

Immortal 1 Top 1.49%

Ascendant Top 8.50%

Diamond Top 21.73%

Platinum Top 41.39%

Gold Top 63.44%

Silver Top 82.09%

Bronze Top 95.52%

Iron Top 100.00%

The Hierarchy (this is how I see it based on the stats):

Gold (The Median): If you are here, you are the statistical mirror of the server. Gameplay wise, Plat is not that far away.

Diamond (Competence): The first sign of non-randomness.

Ascendant (Grinder): High volume, high effort. You're decent.

Immortal 1 (Gatekeeper): The phase transition. You’ve mastered the fundamentals, but you remain the weakest of the best.

Immortal 2 - low Immo 3: The purification. You’ve moved past the gatekeepers and are now refining the micro details => a solid good player.

Immortal 3 400RR+: The elite.

It’s worth noting that Valorant’s ranking system feels significantly more 'inflated' compared to League of Legends.

Top% in LoL (EUW):

Challenger Top 0.01%

GrandMaster Top 0.036%

Master Top 0.896%

Diamond Top 4.90%

Emerald Top 16.90%

Valorant ranks are significantly more inclusive. An Ascendant in Valorant (Top 8.5%) is effectively an Emerald 1/2 player in LoL. A Diamond in Valorant (Top 21%) is common, whereas a Diamond in LoL is Top 5%. Immortal 1 (Top 1.5%) is very close to Diamond 1/2 in LoL (Top ~2-3%).

This doesn't mean Valorant players are 'worse,' but it does mean that Dia/Asc/Immo1 status in Valorant carries less statistical exclusivity than the equivalent tiers in LoL.

What do you guys think about it?",Insight,
