Claw Grip	Heel of palm and fingertips contact	Wrist and fingers	Balance of flick speed and micro-adjustment
Fingertip Grip	Only fingertips contact the mouse	Fingers and micro-wrist movements	Extreme agility and rapid target switching
The palm grip remains favored by those who prioritize clinical consistency and heavy arm movement. By utilizing larger muscle groups, players can maintain steadier aim during tracking exercises, though they may sacrifice the raw speed required for reactive flicking.The claw grip has emerged as the most versatile and common style among professionals, providing a ""locked-in"" feeling that supports repetitive movements during high-pressure engagements.

The fingertip grip, while offering the highest range of motion, is the most physically demanding and can lead to muscle fatigue during extended sessions.In the 2026 meta, where utility has been reduced and pure gunfights have become more frequent, the ability to make rapid micro-corrections with the fingers has seen a resurgence in popularity among entry-fragging specialists.

Ergonomic Posture and Sensory Alignment
Maintaining a neutral ergonomic posture is a prerequisite for long-term skill development. Professional guidelines emphasize a sitting position where the feet are flat on the floor, knees and elbows are bent at approximately 90 degrees, and the spine remains in a poised, upright state.The monitor should be positioned at arm's length, with the top of the screen at or slightly below eye level to minimize neck strain and maintain optimal visual depth perception.

A critical but often overlooked aspect of performance is eye dominance. Approximately 70% of participants are right-eye dominant. Research suggests that right-eye dominant players may benefit from using a left-handed viewmodel to clear the dominant visual field, potentially improving reaction times and situational awareness during chaotic engagements.

Geometric Principles of Engagement and Kinetic Discipline
The synergy between movement and aim is the defining characteristic of elite tactical shooting. In 2026, the ability to manipulate character velocity to achieve instantaneous accuracy has become highly sophisticated.

Movement Accuracy and Counter-Strafing
The accuracy system in modern tactical shooters heavily punishes movement during fire. Achieving a complete stop is necessary for the first-bullet accuracy of weapons like the Vandal or Phantom to take effect.While letting go of movement keys eventually results in stability, the technique of counter-strafing—tapping the opposite direction key to arrest momentum—remains a staple for high-level players.On 128-tick servers, this technique provides a marginal but critical timing advantage, allowing the player to fire sooner than a player who merely releases their keys.

Advanced Techniques: Dead Zoning and Burst Strafing
Dead zoning is a high-level mechanic where a player fires during the infinitesimal window of zero velocity that occurs when changing directions. This allows the player to remain a moving target at almost all times, significantly complicating the enemy's tracking requirements.

Burst strafing serves as an extension of this logic, particularly effective at medium ranges. The player strafes in one direction, counter-strafes, and fires a two-to-three-round burst during the brief pause before instantly switching directions again.This cycle of movement and fire minimizes the window of vulnerability while maximizing damage output.

Tactical Geometry: Slicing the Pie and Angle Advantage
The concept of ""slicing the pie"" involves clearing an angle incrementally by dividing the corner into segments. By pre-aiming each potential enemy location before it is fully exposed, a player can isolate duels and ensure they only face one opponent at a time.

