"I collected all tips that actually worked for me after years of trial and error. This guide might help any player from Iron up to Radiant.

1. System Optimization
1.1 Close every unnecessary background program before playing.
1.2 Achieve a ""clean"" system. Tools like BoosterX will help without reinstalling Windows.
1.3 You can use ""custom Windows builds"", but only use trusted sources.
1.4 Disable GPU hardware acceleration in messengers, browsers, VPN software and so on. This can reduce latency on some GPUs but increases CPU load. Test individually.
1.5 Try MSI Utility V3. It sets peripheral signal processing to high priority. Especially useful for mice and keyboards polling above 1000 Hz.
1.6 Check your RAM frequency in BIOS. After installation, it often defaults to 2133-2400 MHz instead of the advertised speed. Overclocking to 3200 MHz or higher yields a noticeable FPS boost in Valorant.
1.7 Advanced: locking CPU and GPU to a fixed frequency (via overclocking or undervolting) stabilizes frametimes, which directly improves aiming smoothness.
1.8 Watch for thermal throttling. Overheating causes frequency drops, FPS fluctuations, and inconsistent aim. Clean your PC every year. Repaste CPU every 2 years. Add case fans if needed.

2. Hardware
2.1 Bad hardware doesn't remove skill, but eventually you hit a plateau that only an upgrade can break.
2.2 Monitor.

1440p genuinely makes small targets easier to read and track compared to 1080p. Only if your system can push stable FPS to match your refresh rate.

Smoothness gains: 60 → 144 Hz — massive. 144 → 240 Hz — noticeable. 240 → 540 Hz — real but diminishing returns for kill rate. Target 240 Hz as the sweet spot. 2.2.1 Calibrate your monitor's colors using reference images. Helps with faster enemy recognition. 2.2.2 Enable Overdrive in your monitor OSD. Max settings cause inverse ghosting (white trails), blurring moving targets. Optimal range is 50-70%. Verify with UFO Test. 2.3 Keyboard. Membrane to mechanical is night and day. Mechanical to magnetic (Rapid Trigger) is another night and day. Your character stops ""floating"". 2.4 Mouse. Shape that fits your grip matters more than sensor specs. 4000 Hz polling offers a real but subtle advantage. Main priority: sensor must never spin out at your swipe speed. 2.5 Disable ""Enhance Pointer Precision"" in Windows. Valorant uses raw input, but menus and aim trainers don't. The setting distorts sensor data. 2.6 If your crosshair drifts upward or downward during horizontal swipes, the issue is grip ergonomics. Fix it with sensor angle calibration (Angle snapping) or Raw Accel (software for trajectory correction). 2.7 Use DPI of at least 1600. Higher values (3200) further increase aim smoothness. 2.7.1 To keep desktop cursor comfortable at high DPI, adjust Windows pointer speed. This doesn't affect in-game sens in Valorant. Windows speed to in-game sens 1 to 1:

1/11 — 0.24

2/11 — 0.48

3/11 — 0.125

4/11 — 0.25

5/11 — 0.375

6/11 (default) — 0.5 2.8 Mousepad. Keep it clean. Lay it on a hard, flat surface. Size should allow a full 180° turn without lifting the mouse.

3. Posture and Setup
3.1 Straight back isn't just about health — it's about reaction time. Pinched nerves in your neck and shoulders make reaction time higher.
3.2 You need two points of contact for your mouse arm: wrist and elbow/forearm. Your arm should not float. Elbow should be level with or slightly above the desk. If your chair is too low, desk edge pressure kills micro-control.
3.3 Fresh air in the room. Obvious, but your brain needs oxygen.
3.4 Nothing in the way of your mouse movement. Use a mouse bungee/adhesive tape for the wire or better — go wireless.

4. GPU and In-Game Settings
4.1 The combination of NVIDIA Reflex / Anti-Lag + G-Sync / FreeSync is mandatory for smooth gameplay.
4.2 If FPS fluctuates above and below your refresh rate, cap it 3-5 frames below max refresh (e.g., 235 FPS on 240 Hz). This stabilizes frametimes.

5. Your Body
5.1 B-complex vitamins and magnesium directly affect nerve signal conduction and muscle relaxation.
5.2 Physical activity keeps your CNS sharp. Sedentary lifestyle is the enemy of fast reactions.
5.3 Sleep is important. Skill consolidation happens during sleep, not while playing. 30 minutes of practice + 8 hours of sleep > 2 hours of grinding + 5 hours of sleep.

6. Aim Training
6.1 Aim trainers (Aim Lab, KovaaK's) dramatically shorten the path to stable aim.
6.1.1 Use pre-made Valorant playlists. Not all scenarios are useful.
6.1.2 Don't grind the same scenario endlessly. Five repetitions per session is the ceiling. Beyond that, you're building false patterns.
6.1.3 The goal isn't a high score — it's proper technique. Your hand should be as relaxed as possible. Technique varies by scenario type — look up guides from the Voltaic community.
6.2 In-game bot training is non-negotiable. Aim trainers give you ""raw"" aim; bots teach weapon feel and recoil. Best scenario: strafing armored bots with Phantom. Even if your main weapon is Vandal.
6.3 Stop trying to flick faster than you can. Find the speed where you land the first bullet 90% of the time. In a real match, if you speed up 10% you will lose 50% accuracy. Play at your own pace.
6.4 Crosshair placement and movement are part of your aim. A Radiant doesn't aim twice as fast as an Immortal 1. They just put themselves in positions where the kill requires one micro-adjustment and click, not a panic flick.
6.5 Your aim has two components: moving the cursor and predicting when to click. Imagine you're not aiming — you're just pressing M1 the moment the enemy's head crosses your crosshair. If the enemy moves smoothly, prediction is easy. If they AD-spam randomly, prediction is hard. Your job as an aimer is to make your crosshair movement so smooth and predictable that the click timing becomes intuitive.
6.6 Your sensitivity matters less than you think. A good player adapts to almost anything. Pick the sens you can play on for hours without pain or discomfort. Fingers/wrist hurt? Raise sens. Forearm hurts? Lower it. I went from 360 eDPI down to 160 eDPI and eventually settled at 240 eDPI — which happens to be the average among all players.
6.7 The ""prediction"" part of aiming is handled by your Central Nervous System. The CNS fatigues and depletes. Symptoms: freezing on targets, forgetting to click, overshooting, shakiness. Solution: rest, sleep, food. Stop queueing.

7. In-Game Mentality
7.1 Keep yourself calm and don't tilt even when the enemy kills you through smoke 4 times in a row. Shit happens. Just accept it and move on.
7.2 Don't forget that this is just a game. And don't expect your teammates to put the same amount of effort into getting better and winning.

This is the first version of the guide. I'll update and expand it over time. Drop a comment if you disagree with something or want to add your own tips.",Insight,
"Someone that has Valorant as their first shooter game made a post asking for help and I made a wall of text.

Maybe this could help other people.

Yeah, veterans may disagree and talk about caveats, but I guess this text is a good start for a beginner:

“If you're a complete beginner and don't even play shooter games, you have to focus on two different things.

First, you have to focus on your aim.

Second, you have to focus on Valorant.

Training your aim will help you in literally any shooter game you ever play in your life, because having good aim is transferrable to other games that need aiming.

For training the aim part, use 1600 DPI on your mouse. Second, put the in-game sensitivity in a number that when you multiply it by 1600 the result is between 190 and 408.

For instance, I use 1600 and 0,2. This makes the final number be 320 when you multiply both, 320 is between 190 and 408.

You should download some aim trainer like Aim Labs, a really nice and free aim trainer.

The idea of playing Aim Labs is for you to get good at moving your mouse around to wherever you want.

Ok, now, for the Valorant part...

This is absurdly complex, because there's a fucking lot of things you need to learn.

There's game sense, learning how to read the game and what your enemies are gonna do.

There's economy, knowing when to buy, when to save and everything like that.

There's strategizing, deciding what to do.

There's learning your character, knowing what your character does and what you can use to get advantage over your enemies.

There's learning what the other player characters do, to know what your team can do to help you and also what the enemies can do to hurt you.

There's playing as a team, how you should play when you are cooperating with your team.

There's agent roles, what each character role does and what they should be doing in a match.

There's even simple things like learning what to say on voice chat to your team, learning call-outs, learning the names of each place on the map, learning the important info to give to your team and so on.

And we can go on and on about all of this and it's not important for a beginner.

Now, for you, my advice is this:

Do aim labs every day to train your muscle memory using your mouse.

Play a duelist like Phoenix or Raze, being a simple character, or an initiator like Kay/o or Sova, being also simple characters.

Don't play Sentinel or Controller, especially controller. Controller is a too important role to get right and if you get wrong, you can help the enemies too much and fuck your team.

Controllers should be played after you develop game sense, but if you want, Brimstone is good for a beginner.

If you want Sentinels... Sage or Killjoy.

Try each one of those, see who you enjoy most and then you should master this agent. Learn what each utility does so you don't second guess yourself and always know what each of them does.

For learning, I recommend you to search Woohoojin on YouTube. Especially watch this video.

This is the best content for beginners looking to improve. He doesn't post videos anymore after a lot of controversies he had, but that doesn't make his backlog bad.

His videos are amazing for a beginner even if some stuff is outdated, like character abilities and stuff, but a lot of game sense and stuff is really great.

This video above guarantees that you will get to Gold. He also has some videos about movement in the game, learning to get good at movement.

He also has videos about Gunfight Hygiene, which is knowing how to shoot with each weapon depending on the distance you are from the enemies. Like when you have a Vandal and you are shooting like a madman when they are less than 5 meters from you, or strafe tapping when they are far away.

There's a whole playlist with nice guides.

Also, you should learn the basics of economy and this is so basic I can tell you the basics:

If you have 2000 credits, this means no matter what happens, next round you will be able to buy Vandal/Phantom and full shields.

Buying Vandal/Phantom+full shields+full utilities is called a ""Full Buy"".

When you buy stuff, but try to have at least 2k creds, this is a half-buy.

If you don't have creds, your team may call an eco, or economic round, which means you will not buy anything, or at least have 2k to make a full buy next.

There's also a forced round, when you don't have money for a Full Buy, but you buy anyways, buying anything you can, even if you can't full buy and not caring to have 2k creds remaining.

There's also a round called a Full Eco. This is done when some people can buy and others can't. As a team you decide to literally not buy anything. Even if some could, you don't. You don't buy shields, you don't buy weapons or utils. You do this so you guys can have more money for the next rounds.

All of these things must be done together as a team. There's multiple strategies that can be done with all of those, but that's more advanced.

If people are Full Buying, you Full Buy. If they are Half Buying, you Half Buy. If they are on Eco, you also go on Eco or Half Buy if you have too much money. If people talk about a Full Eco, you forget about the shop.

Okay, the game starts, this is a beginners guide to the first three rounds of the game:

You win first round? You have to spend your money on the second round.

When you win the first round, the second round is anti-eco, because the enemies are in an eco round.

You should buy things like a Spectre, Marshall or Bucky along with Full Shields.

You win the second round? The third round is called a Bonus Round. In this round, you shouldn't buy guns or stuff like that. You should do at maximum a Half Buy. The best thing is for you and your teammates to get primary weapons and pistols to drop on the Bonus Round.

If you have a Spectre and a Ghost, drop the Ghost so your ally doesn't need to buy anything.

If you see a Sheriff on the ground TAKE IT! Even if you don't plan on using it, you can drop to your team and this is a really powerful weapon in a Bonus Round.

The idea of the Bonus is to use the weapons you already had and have money for a Full Buy in the fourth round no matter what happens.

You lost the second round? Tough. Now you have to do a Full Eco in the third round.

Okay, now the other side:

You lost the first round?

Full Eco in the second round, because no matter what happens you can full buy in the third.

You won the second?

Really nice! Now Full Buy because they are broken!

(""Broken"" is when you don't have money for a Full Buy)

You did a Full Buy and lost to their Bonus Round?

Oof, rough. Now you guys are broken. Better to do a Full Eco. Even if this means giving them another round, you guys can get more money for the next rounds.

OKAY, THAT'S A GOOD START!

There's a lot more variables and higher rank players may disagree with some of it, but this is basic for a beginner. Follow this and you're a lot better in every 3 first rounds of a half.

Well, I hope this wall of text may help.”

Also, I would add that it's nice for you to look at a guide for the specific agent you decide to play. Woohoojin's videos are good for a beginner in general, but some specifics would be nice to look at other content creators. There's a lot of good ones out there, Hooj was just the one that helped me a lot in general.",Insight,
